mir Kabir Flag.svg}} [[Qajar Iran|Persian Empire]]: Order of the August Portrait, ''28 July 1884''\n* {{Flag|Kingdom of Portugal|1830}}: [[Sash of the Two Orders]] ([[Order of Christ (Portugal)|Christ]] and [[Order of Aviz|Aviz]]), Grand Cross, ''25 May 1881''; [[Sash of the Three Orders|Three Orders]], ''9 April 1896''<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de|last2=Estrela |first2=Paulo Jorge |date=2017 |title=Troca de Decora\u00e7\u00f5es entre os Reis de Portugal e os Imperadores da R\u00fassia|url=https://www.academia.edu/35782766/TROCA_DE_CONDECORA%C3%87%C3%95ES_ENTRE_OS_REIS_DE_PORTUGAL_E_OS_IMPERADORES_DA_R%C3%9ASSIA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Exchange of Decorations between the Kings of Portugal and the Emperors of Russia|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=16 |issue= |page=11 |doi= ||access-date=19 March 2020 }}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Qing dynasty}}: [[Order of the Double Dragon]], Class I Grade I with Diamonds, ''22 April 1896''\n* {{Flag|Kingdom of Romania}}:\n** [[Order of the Star of Romania]], Grand Cross with Collar, ''6 May 1884''\n** [[Order of Carol I]], Collar, ''15 June 1906''<ref name=\"wordpress2\">{{cite web|url=https://royalromania.files.wordpress.com/2009/08/carol-i-nicholas-ii.jpg?w=529|title=Image: carol-i-nicholas-ii.jpg, (500 \u00d7 315 px)|publisher=royalromania.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=6 September 2015}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Kingdom of Serbia}}:\n** [[Order of St. Sava]], Grand Cross\n** [[Order of Kara\u0111or\u0111e's Star]], Grand Cross, ''1910''<ref>{{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Acovi\u0107|first=Dragomir|title=Slava i \u010dast: Odlikovanja me\u0111u Srbima, Srbi me\u0111u odlikovanjima|year=2012|location=Belgrade|publisher=Slu\u017ebeni Glasnik|pages=128}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of Siam (1855).svg}} [[Siam]]: [[Order of the Royal House of Chakri]], Knight, ''20 March 1891''<ref>{{cite journal |author=Royal Thai Government Gazette |date=29 March 1891 |url=http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2433/052/475.PDF  |title=\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e2e\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e35\u0e40\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e25\u0e44\u0e2e\u0e40\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e41\u0e01\u0e23\u0e19\u0e14\u0e4c\u0e14\u0e38\u0e01\u0e0b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e15\u0e2a\u0e4c\u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e23\u0e38\u0e2a\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e22 |language=Thai |access-date=8 May 2019 |author-link=Royal Thai Government Gazette }}</ref> \n* {{Flagcountry|Restoration (Spain)}}: [[Order of the Golden Fleece]], Knight, ''12 April 1883''<ref>{{cite publication|url=http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/issue.vm?id=0000941464&search=&lang=es|chapter=Caballeros de la insigne orden del tois\u00f3n de oro|title=Gu\u00eda Oficial de Espa\u00f1a|last=|first=|date=1887|journal=|accessdate=21 March 2019|page=147|doi=|pmid=}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|Sweden|1844}} {{Flagicon|Norway|1844}} [[Sweden-Norway]]: [[Royal Order of the Seraphim]], Knight with Collar, ''19 May 1883''<ref>{{citation|title=Svensk Rikskalender|year=1909|page=613|url=http://runeberg.org/rikskal/1909/0697.html|via=runeberg.org|accessdate=6 January 2018|language=sv}}</ref>\n* {{Flagcountry|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland}}:\n** [[Order of the Garter]], Knight, ''1 July 1893''<ref name=p69>Shaw, Wm. A. (1906) ''The Knights of England'', '''I''', London, [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924092537418#page/n157/mode/2up p. 69]</ref>\n** [[Royal Victorian Chain]], ''6 September 1904''<ref>Shaw, [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924092537418#page/n507/mode/2up p. 416]</ref>\n** [[Order of the Bath]], Honorary Grand Cross (military), ''20 October 1916''<ref>\"[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/all-notices/content/100840 Russian honours: Emperor Nicholas II of Russia]\". Received 26 November 2018.</ref>\n}}\n\nNicholas II was granted honorary senior rank in a number of foreign armies, reciprocating by extending similar distinctions to a number of his fellow monarchs. These included the Imperial German, Spanish, Italian, Danish and British armies.\n\nHe was [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the [[Royal Scots Greys]] from 1894 until his death. On becoming Colonel-in-Chief he presented the Regiment with a white [[bearskin]], now worn by the bass drummer of the Pipes and Drums of the [[Royal Scots Dragoon Guards]]. The Imperial Russian anthem is still played at dinner nights in the Officers' Mess, where there remains a portrait of the Tsar in Scots Greys uniform. Since his death, the Regiment has worn a black backing behind its cap badge as a symbol of [[mourning]].\n\n===Arms===\n[[File:Lesser CoA of the empire of Russia.svg|upright=1.05|center|thumb|Lesser Coat of Arms of the Empire of Russia and Letter Coat of Arms of the Emperor]]\n\n==Children==\n{| border=1 style=\"border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n!Image!!Name!!Birth!!Death!!Notes\n|-\n|colspan=5|'''By [[Princess Alix of Hesse and by Rhine]]''' (6 June 1872&nbsp;\u2013 17 July 1918, married on 26 November 1894)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Olgachair.jpg|90px]] || [[Grand Duchess Olga Nikolaevna of Russia|Grand Duchess Olga Nikolaevna]]||{{OldStyleDate|15 November|1895|3 November}}||rowspan=\"5\"|[[Execution of the Romanov family|17 July 1918]]||rowspan=\"5\"|Shot, along with their parents, at [[Yekaterinburg]] by the [[Bolshevik]]s\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Tatiana Nikolaevna.jpg|90px]] || [[Grand Duchess Tatiana Nikolaevna of Russia|Grand Duchess Tatiana Nikolaevna]]||{{OldStyleDate|10 June|1897|29 May}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:GrandDuchessMaria1914formal2.jpg|90px]] || [[Grand Duchess Maria Nikolaevna of Russia (1899\u20131918)|Grand Duchess Maria Nikolaevna]]||{{OldStyleDate|26 June|1899|14 June}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Grand Duchess Anastasia Nikolaevna Crisco edit letters removed.jpg|90px]] || [[Grand Duchess Anastasia Nikolaevna of Russia|Grand Duchess Anastasia Nikolaevna]]||{{OldStyleDate|18 June|1901|5 June}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Alexei Nikolaevich, Tsarevich of Russia.jpg|90px]] || [[Alexei Nikolaevich, Tsarevich of Russia|Tsarevich Alexei Nikolaevich]]||{{OldStyleDate|12 August|1904|30 July}}\n|}\n\n== Wealth ==\nEstimates of Nicholas II's personal wealth have been vastly exaggerated. As ''Emperor of All The Russias'', and an [[Autocracy|autocrat]], the resources under his command were virtually incalculable. However, the vast majority of this was owned by the state as [[Crown property]]; the Romanov family's ''personal wealth'' was only a small fraction of this. As monarch, the income of Nicholas was 24 million gold [[Ruble|roubles]] per annum: this derived from a yearly allowance from the Treasury, and from the profits of Crown farmland.<ref name=\"Massie, Robert K. 1967, p64\">Massie, Robert K. ''Nicholas and Alexandra'', New York, Atheneum, 1967, p64</ref> From this income, he had to fund staff, the upkeep of imperial palaces and imperial theatres, annuities for the royal family, pensions, bequests, and other outgoings. \"Before the end of the year, the Tsar was usually penniless; sometimes he reached this embarrassing state by autumn.\"<ref name=\"Massie, Robert K. 1967, p64\"/> According to the Grand Marshal of the Court, Count Paul Benckendorff, the family's total financial resources amounted to between 12.5 and 17.5 million roubles.<ref>Clarke, William ''The Lost Fortune of the Tsars'', St. Martin's Griffin; Reprint edition, 1996, p101.</ref> As a comparison, Prince Felix Yusupov estimated his family's worth in real estate holdings alone as amounting to 50 million gold roubles.<ref>Ferrand, Jacques ''Les Princes Youssoupoff & les comtes Soumarkoff Elston'', Paris 1991</ref>\n\n== Documentaries and films ==\n{{See also|List of films about the Romanovs}}\nSeveral films about Nicholas II and his family have been made, including ''[[Anastasia (1956 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1956), ''[[Nicholas and Alexandra]]'' (1971), ''[[Anastasia: The Mystery of Anna]]'' (1986), ''[[Rasputin: Dark Servant of Destiny]]'' (1996 [[HBO]]), ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1997), and two Russian adaptations ''[[Assassin of the Tsar]]'' (1991) and ''[[The Romanovs: An Imperial Family]]'' (2000).\nIn 2017 the film ''[[Matilda (2017 film)]]'' was released. ''[[The Last Czars]]'' was released by Netflix in 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Saints}}\n* [[Bibliography of the Russian Revolution and Civil War]]\n* [[Emperor railway station in Pushkin town]]\n\n==Note==\n* {{note|dates|O.S./N.S.}}Over the course of Nicholas's life, two calendars were used: the [[Old Style and New Style dates|Old Style]] [[Julian Calendar]] and the [[Old Style and New Style dates|New Style]] [[Gregorian Calendar]]. Russia switched from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar on 1 February (O.S.) / 14 February (N.S.) 1918.\n* {{notelist|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n*{{cite book|ref=Figes|authorlink=Orlando Figes|author=Figes, Orlando|title=A People's Tragedy: The Russian Revolution 1891\u20131924|publisher=The Bodley Head|year=2015}}\n*{{cite book|ref=King1994|authorlink=Greg King (author)|author=King, Greg|title=The Last Empress |publisher=Birch Lane Press|year= 1994}}\n*{{cite book|ref=King2006|authorlink=Greg King (author)|author=King, Greg|title=The Court of the Last Czar: Pomp, Power and Pageantry in the Reign of Nicholas II|year=2006|publisher=John Wiley & Sons}}\n*{{cite book | last = Kowner| first = Rotem|authorlink=Rotem Kowner| year = 2006 | title = Historical Dictionary of the Russo-Japanese War|publisher=The Scarecrow Press| isbn=978-0-8108-4927-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lieven|first=Dominic|title=Nicholas II, Emperor of all the Russias|publisher=Pimlico|place=London|year=1993|ref=harv|authorlink=Dominic Lieven}}\n* Massie, Robert, ''Nicholas and Alexandra'', London: Pan Books, 1967. [https://archive.org/details/nicholasalexandr00mass_0 online free to borrow]\n*{{cite book|ref=Massie1995|authorlink=Robert K. Massie|author=Massie, Robert K. |title=The Fa