nd]]|years=1894\u20131917}}\n{{S-vac|next=[[Prince Frederick Charles of Hesse|Frederick Charles]]|as=king-elect}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-pre|}}\n{{S-new|loss|reason=Empire abolished}}\n{{S-tul|title=[[Emperor of Russia]]|years=1917|reason=[[February Revolution|Empire abolished in 1917]]}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Grand Duke Nikolai Nikolaevich of Russia (1856\u20131929)|Nikolai Nikolaevich]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Russian emperors}}\n{{Russian grand dukes}}\n{{Supreme Commanders of the Russian Army during WWI}}\n{{Russian Revolution 1917}}\n{{Pretenders to the Russian throne since 1917}}\n{{Murder of the Romanovs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicholas 02}}\n[[Category:Nicholas II of Russia| ]]\n[[Category:1868 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Russian monarchs]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian monarchs]]\n[[Category:19th-century Polish monarchs]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish monarchs]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:British field marshals]]\n[[Category:Burials at Peter and Paul Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Russia]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox people executed by the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Executed monarchs]]\n[[Category:House of Romanov]]\n[[Category:Leaders ousted by a coup]]\n[[Category:Monarchs who abdicated]]\n[[Category:Murdered Russian monarchs]]\n[[Category:Assassinations in Russia]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox monarchs]]\n[[Category:Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907]]\n[[Category:Executed people from Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Andrew]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Alexander Nevsky]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the White Eagle (Russia)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Anna, 1st class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Saint Stanislaus (Russian), 1st class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Vladimir, 4th class]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the House and Merit Order of Peter Frederick Louis]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Rising Sun with Paulownia Flowers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Golden Fleece of Spain]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Christ (Portugal)|3]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Aviz|3]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Saint James of the Sword|3]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the White Falcon]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Ludwigsorden]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of Saint Hubert]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Saint Alexander (Bulgaria)]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Crown (W\u00fcrttemberg)]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Black Eagle]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Red Eagle]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the House Order of Fidelity]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Saint Stephen of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Grand Croix of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Southern Cross]]\n[[Category:Extra Knights Companion of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of the Dannebrog]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Seal of Solomon]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Double Dragon]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Victorian Chain]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Carol I]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Medal of Military Valor]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the House Order of the Wendish Crown]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox royal saints]]\n[[Category:Rulers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Russian anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Russian emperors]]\n[[Category:Russian grand dukes]]\n[[Category:Russian saints of the Eastern Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Russian people of the Russo-Japanese War]]\n[[Category:People of the Russian Revolution]]\n[[Category:Russian people of World War I]]\n[[Category:Victims of Red Terror in Soviet Russia]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Russia]]\n[[Category:People of the 1905 Russian Revolution]]\n[[Category:People executed by Russia by firing squad]]\n[[Category:Executed Russian people]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Russia]]\n[[Category:20th-century murdered monarchs]]\n[[Category:Dethroned monarchs]]\n[[Category:Tsesarevichs of Russia]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "name_user": "175.37.32.56", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFamily background)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_II_of_Russia"}
{"title_page": "American India Foundation", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = American India Foundation\n| image = \n| logo = https://mk0lafuliji23yjknmic.kinstacdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/AIF_logo.png\n| type = [[Charitable trust]]\n| founded_date = 2001\n| founder = President [[Bill Clinton]], Lata Krishnan, [[Rajat Gupta]], [[Victor Menezes]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.synergos.org/globalgivingmatters/features/0201aif.htm | title= Long Distance Philanthropy Brings Donors Closer to Home | accessdate=2008-11-20}}</ref>\n| key_people = Lata Krishnan (Co-Chair)<br>Harit Talwar (Co-Chair)<br>Nishant Pandey (CEO)<br> Mathew Joseph (India Country Director)\n| location_city = \n| location_country = \n| location = [[New York City|New York]] / [[Delhi]]\n| area_served = [[India]] [[USA]]\n| focus = [[Education]], [[Livelihood]], [[Public health|Public Health]]\n| method = \n| owner = \n| Non-profit_slogan = \n| homepage = [http://AIF.org/ AIF.org]\n}}\n\nThe '''American India Foundation''' (AIF, founded 2001) is a [[nonprofit]] [[United States|American]] organization that is devoted to accelerating social and economic change in [[India]]. The AIF has partnered with 227 of India's NGOs to build a trusted network for implementation, scale, and sustainability while raising over $125 million since its inception.<ref name=\"www.aif.org\">http://www.aif.org</ref> It is one of the largest secular, non-partisan American organizations supporting development work in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macfound.org/grantees/2381/|title=American India Foundation - MacArthur Foundation|website=macfound.org|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAIF is committed to catalyzing social and economic change in [[India]], and building a lasting bridge between the [[United States]] and India through high-impact interventions in [[education]], [[livelihood]]s, [[public health]], and leadership development. Working closely with [[Local community|local communities]], AIF partners with [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] to develop and test innovative solutions and with governments to create and scale sustainable impact.\n\nIt also runs the Service Corps Fellowship, renamed the William J. Clinton Fellowship for Service to India on May 11, 2009, which sends skilled young Americans in an immersive [[Volunteering|volunteer service program]] training and placing young professionals to support development organizations across India for 10 months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.profellow.com/announcements/william-j-clinton-fellowship-for-service-in-india-learning-about-grassroots-development-and-inclusive-leadership-in-india/|title=William J. Clinton Fellowship for Service in India: Learning about Grassroots Development and Inclusive Leadership in India {{!}} ProFellow|date=2018-11-12|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Through this program, Fellows and host organizations form dynamic cross-cultural partnerships to exchange knowledge and skills, build capacity, and foster learning to fulfill our joint commitment to improve the lives of India's most marginalized communities.\n\n==History==\nFounded in 2001 at the initiative of [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Bill Clinton]] following a suggestion from [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] by a group of [[Indian-American]]s responding to the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake|Gujarat earthquake]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928195246/http://www.clintonpresidentialcenter.org/061702-sp-cf-rr-gn-gl-irq-afg-prk-rwa-bra-sp-wjc-addresses-council-on-foreign-relations.htm|title=Clinton Presidential Center \"Council on Foreign Relations, 2002\"|date=2007-09-28|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> AIF has impacted the lives of 5.6 million of India's poor by providing access to high-quality education, formal sector [[employment]] for urban youth and [[rickshaw]] drivers, and public health services to protect the health of mothers and their children, while building the next generation of global leaders through service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4159765|title=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4159765|website=guidestar.org|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nWith offices in New York and [[California]], twelve chapters across the U.S., and India operations headquartered in New Delhi, AIF is transforming lives across 24 [[States and union territories of India|states of India]] while addressing these issues on a regional, country, and international scale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/american-india-foundation-and-westbridge-capital-announce-four-year-partnership-300889243.html|title=American India Foundation and WestBridge Capital Announce Four-year Partnership|last=Foundation|first=American India|website=prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n== Mission and values ==\nThe mission of AIF is to catalyze social and economic change in India. AIF is focused on improving lives of India's [[underprivileged]], especially women and young, through:\n\n* connecting American and Indian people, civil society and expertise;\n* multi-pronged scale interventions in education, health and livelihood for an assault on poverty\n* an apolitical and inclusive view of the Indian society\n\nAIF's vision is to contribute to building an India where all people can gain access to affordable education, health care and livelihood opportunities, and where all Indians can realize their full potential. AIF engages, informs, and inspires those passionate about India by building a trusted bridge and secure channel for philanthropic funding from the United States and other regions across the world, as well as effective investment in the most innovative and scalable projects in India. AIF upholds the principles of secularism, transparency, and accountability in all of its activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aif.org/about/mission-vision-and-values/|title=Mission Vision and Values \u2013 AIF|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n== AIF's Emergency Response ==\nIn cases of major national disasters in India, AIF has been involved in relief and rehabilitation efforts. It has undertaken several campaigns for relief and rehabilitation:\n\n# In 2001, after the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake|Gujarat earthquake]]\n# In 2004, after the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|tsunami]]\n# In 2005, after the [[2005 Kashmir earthquake|Kashmir earthquake]]\n#In 2019, after the [[2019 Pulwama attack|Pulwama attack]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/kirenrijiju/status/1126045031888850944?lang=en|title=India's Minister of State for Home Affairs|last=Rijiju|first=Kiren|date=2019-05-08|website=@kirenrijiju|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n#In 2020, during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aif.org/american-india-foundation-launches-covid-19-response-effort/|title=American India Foundation Launches COVID-19 Response Effort \u2013 AIF|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAIF takes a multi-phased approach to disaster relief: relief, reconstruction and rehabilitation. AIF's focus is the long-term rehabilitation of communities, and it dedicates most of its resources to this phase. In [[Gujarat]] and [[Tamil Nadu]], AIF funded organizations in affected communities for up to three years following the earthquake so that NGO partners could identify long-term solutions to improve the lives of people affected by disaster.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aifoundation.org/about/emergencies.htm |title=AIF Emergency Response |accessdate=2008-11-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522164957/http://www.aifoundation.org/about/emergencies.htm |archivedate=2008-05-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Programs ==\n\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/education/learning-and-migration-program/ Learning and Migration Program (LAMP)]''' provides access to quality education opportunities to children in areas of seasonal migration, while also advocating to communities and governments the universal right to education.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/education/digital-equalizer/ Digital Equalizer]''' utilizes technology to bridge the educational and digital divide in India by transforming under-resourced schools into dynamic places to teach and learn through collaborative, project-based learning.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/livelihoods/market-aligned-skills-training/ Market Aligned Skills Training (MAST)]''' provides underprivileged youth with skills training and access to formal employment opportunities.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/livelihoods/ability-based-livelihood-empowerment/ Ability Based Livelihoods Empowerment (ABLE)]''' trains persons with disabilities and facilitates their entry into the job market through advocacy, promoting inclusive growth in India.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/livelihoods/rickshaw-sangh/ Rickshaw Sangh]''' enables rickshaw drivers to own their vehicles by accessing formal credit through collectives, creating a life-changing asset and formalizing the profession through access to key social benefits. \n* '''[https://aif.org/fellowship/ William J. Clinton Fellowship for Service in India]''' builds the next generation of service leadership committed to lasting change for underprivileged communities across India, while strengthening the civil sector landscape to be more efficient and effective.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/public-health/ Maternal and Newborn Survival Initiative (MANSI)]''' utilizes a public-private partnership model to reduce maternal and child mortality by providing resources and support, thus empowering local communities to care for their mothers and children while improving the local health systems.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aif.org/ American India Foundation]\n*[https://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.programs&orgid=8941 Charity Navigator]\n*[https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4159765 GuideStar] \n*\n\n[[Category:Development charities based in the United States]]\n[[Category:South Asian American organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Foreign charities operating in India]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Primary sources|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = American India Foundation\n| image = \n| logo = https://mk0lafuliji23yjknmic.kinstacdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/AIF_logo.png\n| type = [[Charitable trust]]\n| founded_date = 2001\n| founder = President [[Bill Clinton]], Lata Krishnan, [[Rajat Gupta]], [[Victor Menezes]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.synergos.org/globalgivingmatters/features/0201aif.htm | title= Long Distance Philanthropy Brings Donors Closer to Home | accessdate=2008-11-20}}</ref>\n| key_people = Lata Krishnan (Co-Chair)<br>Harit Talwar (Co-Chair)<br>Nishant Pandey (CEO)<br> Mathew Joseph (India Country Director)\n| location_city = \n| location_country = \n| location = [[New York City|New York]] / [[Delhi]]\n| area_served = [[India]] [[USA]]\n| focus = [[Education]], [[Livelihood]], [[Public health|Public Health]]\n| method = \n| owner = \n| Non-profit_slogan = \n| homepage = [http://AIF.org/ AIF.org]\n}}\n\nThe '''American India Foundation''' (AIF, founded 2001) is a [[nonprofit]] [[United States|American]] organization that is devoted to accelerating social and economic change in [[India]]. The AIF has partnered with 227 of India's NGOs to build a trusted network for implementation, scale, and sustainability while raising over $125 million since its inception.<ref name=\"www.aif.org\">http://www.aif.org</ref> It is one of the largest secular, non-partisan American organizations supporting development work in India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macfound.org/grantees/2381/|title=American India Foundation - MacArthur Foundation|website=www.macfound.org|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>.\n\nAIF is committed to catalyzing social and economic change in [[India]], and building a lasting bridge between the [[United States]] and India through high-impact interventions in [[education]], [[Livelihood|livelihoods]], [[public health]], and leadership development. Working closely with [[Local community|local communities]], AIF partners with [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] to develop and test innovative solutions and with governments to create and scale sustainable impact. \n\nIt also runs the Service Corps Fellowship, renamed the William J. Clinton Fellowship for Service to India on May 11, 2009, which sends skilled young Americans in an immersive [[Volunteering|volunteer service program]] training and placing young professionals to support development organizations across India for 10 months<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.profellow.com/announcements/william-j-clinton-fellowship-for-service-in-india-learning-about-grassroots-development-and-inclusive-leadership-in-india/|title=William J. Clinton Fellowship for Service in India: Learning about Grassroots Development and Inclusive Leadership in India {{!}} ProFellow|date=2018-11-12|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>. Through this program, Fellows and host organizations form dynamic cross-cultural partnerships to exchange knowledge and skills, build capacity, and foster learning to fulfill our joint commitment to improve the lives of India's most marginalized communities.\n\n=='''History'''==\nFounded in 2001 at the initiative of [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Bill Clinton]] following a suggestion from [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] by a group of [[Indian-American]]s responding to the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake|Gujarat earthquake]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928195246/http://www.clintonpresidentialcenter.org/061702-sp-cf-rr-gn-gl-irq-afg-prk-rwa-bra-sp-wjc-addresses-council-on-foreign-relations.htm|title=Clinton Presidential Center \"Council on Foreign Relations, 2002\"|date=2007-09-28|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>, AIF has impacted the lives of 5.6 million of India's poor by providing access to high-quality education, formal sector [[employment]] for urban youth and [[rickshaw]] drivers, and public health services to protect the health of mothers and their children, while building the next generation of global leaders through service<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4159765|title=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4159765|website=www.guidestar.org|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>. \n\nWith offices in New York and [[California]], twelve chapters across the U.S., and India operations headquartered in New Delhi, AIF is transforming lives across 24 [[States and union territories of India|states of India]] while addressing these issues on a regional, country, and international scale<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/american-india-foundation-and-westbridge-capital-announce-four-year-partnership-300889243.html|title=American India Foundation and WestBridge Capital Announce Four-year Partnership|last=Foundation|first=American India|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>.\n\n== '''Mission and values''' ==\nThe mission of AIF is to catalyze social and economic change in India. AIF is focused on improving lives of India's [[underprivileged]], especially women and young, through:\n\n* connecting American and Indian people, civil society and expertise;\n* multi-pronged scale interventions in education, health and livelihood for an assault on poverty\n* an apolitical and inclusive view of the Indian society\n\nAIF's vision is to contribute to building an India where all people can gain access to affordable education, health care and livelihood opportunities, and where all Indians can realize their full potential. AIF engages, informs, and inspires those passionate about India by building a trusted bridge and secure channel for philanthropic funding from the United States and other regions across the world, as well as effective investment in the most innovative and scalable projects in India. AIF upholds the principles of secularism, transparency, and accountability in all of its activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aif.org/about/mission-vision-and-values/|title=Mission Vision and Values \u2013 AIF|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n== '''AIF's Emergency Response''' ==\nIn cases of major national disasters in India, AIF has been involved in relief and rehabilitation efforts. It has undertaken several campaigns for relief and rehabilitation:\n\n# In 2001, after the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake|Gujarat earthquake]]\n# In 2004, after the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|tsunami]]\n# In 2005, after the [[2005 Kashmir earthquake|Kashmir earthquake]]\n#In 2019, after the [[2019 Pulwama attack|Pulwama attack]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/kirenrijiju/status/1126045031888850944?lang=en|title=India's Minister of State for Home Affairs|last=Rijiju|first=Kiren|date=2019-05-08|website=@kirenrijiju|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n#In 2020, during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aif.org/american-india-foundation-launches-covid-19-response-effort/|title=American India Foundation Launches COVID-19 Response Effort \u2013 AIF|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nAIF takes a multi-phased approach to disaster relief: relief, reconstruction and rehabilitation. AIF's focus is the long-term rehabilitation of communities, and it dedicates most of its resources to this phase. In [[Gujarat]] and [[Tamil Nadu]], AIF funded organizations in affected communities for up to three years following the earthquake so that NGO partners could identify long-term solutions to improve the lives of people affected by disaster.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aifoundation.org/about/emergencies.htm |title=AIF Emergency Response |accessdate=2008-11-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522164957/http://www.aifoundation.org/about/emergencies.htm |archivedate=2008-05-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\n== '''Programs''' ==\n\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/education/learning-and-migration-program/ Learning and Migration Program (LAMP)]''' provides access to quality education opportunities to children in areas of seasonal migration, while also advocating to communities and governments the universal right to education.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/education/digital-equalizer/ Digital Equalizer]''' utilizes technology to bridge the educational and digital divide in India by transforming under-resourced schools into dynamic places to teach and learn through collaborative, project-based learning.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/livelihoods/market-aligned-skills-training/ Market Aligned Skills Training (MAST)]''' provides underprivileged youth with skills training and access to formal employment opportunities.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/livelihoods/ability-based-livelihood-empowerment/ Ability Based Livelihoods Empowerment (ABLE)]''' trains persons with disabilities and facilitates their entry into the job market through advocacy, promoting inclusive growth in India.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/livelihoods/rickshaw-sangh/ Rickshaw Sangh]''' enables rickshaw drivers to own their vehicles by accessing formal credit through collectives, creating a life-changing asset and formalizing the profession through access to key social benefits. \n* '''[https://aif.org/fellowship/ William J. Clinton Fellowship for Service in India]''' builds the next generation of service leadership committed to lasting change for underprivileged communities across India, while strengthening the civil sector landscape to be more efficient and effective.\n* '''[https://aif.org/our-work/public-health/ Maternal and Newborn Survival Initiative (MANSI)]''' utilizes a public-private partnership model to reduce maternal and child mortality by providing resources and support, thus empowering local communities to care for their mothers and children while improving the local health systems.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aif.org/ American India Foundation]\n*[https://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.programs&orgid=8941 Charity Navigator]\n*[https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4159765 GuideStar] \n*\n\n[[Category:Development charities based in the United States]]\n[[Category:South Asian American organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Foreign charities operating in India]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=www. \u2192 website= (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_India_Foundation"}
{"title_page": "Ted Knight (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n'''Edward Robert Knight''' (13 June 1933 \u2013 30 March 2020) was a local politician in [[London]], England who was leader of [[Lambeth London Borough Council]] from 1978.<ref name=\"Ashley\">Cathy Ashley \"Ted Knight\" in Greg Rosen (ed.) ''Dictionary of Labour Biography'', London: Politicos, 2001, p.342-43</ref>\n\n==Lambeth Council==\nTed Knight was active in the Labour Party from a young age but was expelled from the Party in 1956 following a purge of the Trotskyist [[Workers' Revolutionary Party (UK)#Socialist Labour League|Socialist Labour League]] (SLL)<ref name=\"Ashley\"/>. Knight was re-admitted to the Norwood Constituency Labour Party in 1970, despite suspicions by some members that he retained his links with the proscribed SLL. In Norwood Labour Party Knight met [[Ken Livingstone]], later Leader of the [[Greater London Council]] and [[Mayor of London]], and the two formed an alliance to influence the selection of candidates in Norwood for the council elections in 1974. After that, they jostled for the leadership of the left within the Labour Group on Lambeth Borough Council but Livingstone's later move to Camden in North London left the way open for Knight to become the leading left-winger within the Labour Group and Leader of the Council.\n\nWhen the Conservative Government took powers through the [[Rates Act 1984]] to limit the budgets of local councils, several left-wing Labour councils organised a [[rate-capping rebellion|rebellion]] in which they refused to set a budget. All the councils eventually backed down except [[Liverpool City Council]] and Lambeth. The district auditor found that the council had lost interest on tax payments as a result, which was held to be due to the \"wilful misconduct\" of Knight and 31 other councillors. Each was required to repay the amount of lost interest in a surcharge and banned from holding office for five years. The Labour Party's leader, [[Neil Kinnock]], blamed local leaders like Ted Knight and [[Linda Bellos]] from Lambeth, for bringing the [[Labour Party UK|Labour Party]] into disrepute.\n\nPrior to the 1987 general election, Knight was a potential candidate for [[Coventry North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry North East]]: a runner-up at the [[Constituency Labour Party]] selection meeting, he lost out to [[John Hughes (Coventry North East MP)|John Hughes]].\n\n==After Lambeth==\nKnight took a break from politics after being expelled from office as a result of the [[Rate-capping rebellion]]. He pursued various business interests and remained treasurer of the town hall social club until it closed in 1994. He remained active within his union, [[Unite (trade union)|Unite]].\n\nKnight was elected to the National Committee of the [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)]] at their AGM on 17 November 2007. \n\nAfter the election of Jeremy Corbyn as leader of the Labour Party, Knight once again became active in Lambeth Labour, securing the post of Branch Chair in Gipsy Hill ward in November 2016.  \n\nKnight died in March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonnell |first1=John |title=A giant of our movement |url=https://www.john-mcdonnell.net/news/2020/03/30/a-giant-of-our-movement/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=John McDonnell MP |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite interview\n| last           =Knight\n| first          =Ted\n| interviewer    =Jeff Rodrigues\n| title          =Ted Knight interviewed by Jeff Rodrigues\n| url            =http://www.amielandmelburn.org.uk/collections/mt/pdf/81_01_11.pdf\n| format         =PDF\n| work           =[[Marxism Today]]\n| date           =January 1981\n\n| pages          =11&ndash;16\n| access-date    =2016-11-29\n| publisher      =[[Communist Party of Great Britain|CPGB]]\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knight, Ted}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n'''Edward Robert''' \"'''Ted'''\" '''Knight''' (13 June 1933 \u2013 30 March 2020) was a local politician in [[London]], England who was leader of [[Lambeth London Borough Council]] from 1978.<ref name=\"Ashley\">Cathy Ashley \"Ted Knight\" in Greg Rosen (ed.) ''Dictionary of Labour Biography'', London: Politicos, 2001, p.342-43</ref>\n\n==Lambeth Council==\nTed Knight was active in the Labour Party from a young age but was expelled from the Party in 1956 following a purge of the Trotskyist [[Workers' Revolutionary Party (UK)#Socialist Labour League|Socialist Labour League]] (SLL)<ref name=\"Ashley\"/>. Knight was re-admitted to the Norwood Constituency Labour Party in 1970, despite suspicions by some members that he retained his links with the proscribed SLL. In Norwood Labour Party Knight met [[Ken Livingstone]], later Leader of the [[Greater London Council]] and [[Mayor of London]], and the two formed an alliance to influence the selection of candidates in Norwood for the council elections in 1974. After that, they jostled for the leadership of the left within the Labour Group on Lambeth Borough Council but Livingstone's later move to Camden in North London left the way open for Knight to become the leading left-winger within the Labour Group and Leader of the Council.\n\nWhen the Conservative Government took powers through the [[Rates Act 1984]] to limit the budgets of local councils, several left-wing Labour councils organised a [[rate-capping rebellion|rebellion]] in which they refused to set a budget. All the councils eventually backed down except [[Liverpool City Council]] and Lambeth. The district auditor found that the council had lost interest on tax payments as a result, which was held to be due to the \"wilful misconduct\" of Knight and 31 other councillors. Each was required to repay the amount of lost interest in a surcharge and banned from holding office for five years. The Labour Party's leader, [[Neil Kinnock]], blamed local leaders like Ted Knight and [[Linda Bellos]] from Lambeth, for bringing the [[Labour Party UK|Labour Party]] into disrepute.\n\nPrior to the 1987 general election, Knight was a potential candidate for [[Coventry North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry North East]]: a runner-up at the [[Constituency Labour Party]] selection meeting, he lost out to [[John Hughes (Coventry North East MP)|John Hughes]].\n\n==After Lambeth==\nKnight took a break from politics after being expelled from office as a result of the [[Rate-capping rebellion]]. He pursued various business interests and remained treasurer of the town hall social club until it closed in 1994. He remained active within his union, [[Unite (trade union)|Unite]].\n\nKnight was elected to the National Committee of the [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)]] at their AGM on 17 November 2007. \n\nAfter the election of Jeremy Corbyn as leader of the Labour Party, Knight once again became active in Lambeth Labour, securing the post of Branch Chair in Gipsy Hill ward in November 2016.  \n\nKnight died in March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonnell |first1=John |title=A giant of our movement |url=https://www.john-mcdonnell.net/news/2020/03/30/a-giant-of-our-movement/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=John McDonnell MP |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite interview\n| last           =Knight\n| first          =Ted\n| interviewer    =Jeff Rodrigues\n| title          =Ted Knight interviewed by Jeff Rodrigues\n| url            =http://www.amielandmelburn.org.uk/collections/mt/pdf/81_01_11.pdf\n| format         =PDF\n| work           =[[Marxism Today]]\n| date           =January 1981\n\n| pages          =11&ndash;16\n| access-date    =2016-11-29\n| publisher      =[[Communist Party of Great Britain|CPGB]]\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knight, Ted}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Leaders of local authorities of England]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:NICKNAME", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ted_Knight_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "By\u00e5sen HE", "text_new": "{{Infobox handball club\n| clubname    = By\u00e5sen H\u00e5ndball Elite\n| fullname    = By\u00e5sen H\u00e5ndball Elite\n| short name  = By\u00e5sen HE\n| image       = Byasen.svg\n| founded     = 1921\n| ground      = [[Trondheim Spektrum]], [[Trondheim]]\n| capacity    = 8,600 (since 2019)\n| chairman    = Oddvar Aardahl\n| coach       = Roger Kvannli\n| league      = [[Eliteserien (women's handball)|Eliteserien]]\n| season      = 2018\u201319\n| position    = 6th\n| website     = http://byaasen.no/\n| colour1     = red\n| colour2     = white\n| pattern_la1 = | pattern_b1 =  | pattern_ra1 = | leftarm1 = EF2B2D | body1 = EF2B2D | rightarm1 = EF2B2D | shorts1 = 2B345B | socks1 = FFFFFF\n<!-- Away colours -->\n| pattern_la2 = | pattern_b2 = | pattern_ra2 = | leftarm2 = FFFFFF | body2 = FFFFFF | rightarm2 = FFFFFF | shorts2 = 2B345B | socks2 = FFFFFF\n}}\n'''By\u00e5sen H\u00e5ndball Elite''' is the women's [[handball]] team of the Norwegian multi-sports club [[By\u00e5sen IL]] based in [[Trondheim]]. The team plays in [[Eliteserien (women's handball)|Eliteserien]], the top division in the country, since its promotion in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://byaasen.no/artikkel/11352|title=By\u00e5sens Historie|trans-title=History of By\u00e5sen|publisher=By\u00e5sen HE official website|date=June 2010|accessdate=2 October 2011|language=Norwegian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531000051/http://byaasen.no/artikkel/11352#|archive-date=2011-05-31|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe team's first success came as a third division club, when in 1980 it won the silver medal in the national cup. Among its successes are four domestic league and four domestic cup titles, and the club also has a good reputation in the continental arena, having reached the latest stage of the European cup competitions, including the EHF Cup Winners' Cup final in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://byaasen.no/artikkel/134687|title=Meritter|trans-title=Merits|publisher=By\u00e5sen HE official website|date=July 2011|accessdate=2 October 2011|language=Norwegian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502124925/http://byaasen.no/artikkel/134687#|archive-date=2012-05-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n*'''Norwegian Championship''':\n**''Winners'': 1984/1985, 1985/1986, 1987/1988, 1988/1989\n*'''Norwegian Cup''':\n**''Winners'': 1988, 1989, 1991, 2007\n**''Finalist'': 2006, 2008, 2009\n*'''[[EHF Women's Cup Winners' Cup|EHF Cup Winners' Cup]]''':\n**''Finalist'': [[2006\u201307 EHF Women's Cup Winner's Cup|2006/2007]]\n\n==European record ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Season\n! Competition\n! Round\n! Club\n! 1st leg\n! 2nd leg\n! Aggregate\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" bgcolor=white|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[2016\u201317 Women's EHF Cup|2016\u201317]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[Women's EHF Cup|EHF Cup]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2016\u201317 Women's EHF Cup#Round 1|R1]]\n| {{flagicon|SLO}} [[RK Zagorje]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 32\u201320\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 25\u201325\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''57\u201345'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2016\u201317 Women's EHF Cup#Round 2|R2]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Tertnes HE]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 33\u201327\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 29\u201326\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''62\u201353'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2016\u201317 Women's EHF Cup#Round 3|R3]]\n| {{flagicon|ROM}} [[HC Dun\u0103rea Br\u0103ila]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 24\u201325\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 34\u201323\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''58\u201348'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2016\u201317 Women's EHF Cup#Group C|Group C]]\n| {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Rostov-Don]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 29\u201324\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 21\u201335\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4th place\n|-\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[SG BBM Bietigheim]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 23\u201